name: heptylcyclopentane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic unit, cyclopentane, has a melting point around -94°C. Adding a heptyl (7-carbon alkyl) group generally increases the melting point due to the increased molecular weight and slight increase in the van der Waals forces, but since it's an alkyl group, the increase is not substantial. The heptyl group might increase the melting point by approximately 20°C to 40°C.

name: heptylcyclopentane
source: American Petroleum Institute. Research Project 44; Selected Values of Properties of Hydrocarbons and Related Compounds. Texas A & M University; College Station; TX; 1973.
Reason: The basic unit, cyclopentane, has a melting point around -94°C. The addition of a heptyl (7-carbon alkyl) group should raise the melting point due to increased molecular weight and van der Waals forces. Alkyl groups are not very polar and do not contribute significantly to intermolecular hydrogen bonding, hence the increment is relatively moderate. The estimated increase in melting point is around 41°C, obtained by considering the incremental increase of approximately 5-6°C per methylene unit in a normal alkane.
